      {
        "id": "https://openalex.org/W7163370788",
        "doi": "10.1016/j.engstruct.2026.123049",
        "title": "Design variables influencing the seismic performance of buckling-restrained braced frame building archetypes and simplified tools to estimate their demands",
        "published": "2026-06-03",
        "url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.engstruct.2026.123049",
        "authors": [
          "S. Sistla",
          "R. Chandramohan",
          "T.J. Sullivan"
        ],
        "institutions": [
          "University of Canterbury"
        ],
        "journal": "Engineering Structures",
        "abstract": "This study examines and quantifies the influence of key design variables like drift limit, brace configuration, brace angle, etc. on the seismic performance of buckling-restrained braced frame (BRBF) buildings. The effect of these design variables on peak storey drift ratio (PSDR), peak floor acceleration (PFA), mean annual frequency of collapse ( λ c ), and expected annual loss (EAL) is characterised using 25 BRBF building archetypes. Measures that increase structural stiffness, such as designing to lower drift limits and using moment-resisting beam–column connections, are shown to mitigate collapse risk and economic losses. Most of the buildings designed to drift limits above 2.0 % following conventional practice failed to meet the collapse performance objective of λ c < 1 0 − 4 prescribed by the New Zealand seismic design standard. Even fewer buildings met the loss target of EAL < 0.1 % prescribed by the NZ low-damage seismic design guidelines. Finally, simplified PSDR and PFA prediction tools are developed to enable demand-targeted BRBF structural and non-structural design for enhanced seismic resilience. These tools achieve R 2 = 0 . 95 and prediction errors below 10 %. When compared to existing demand prediction methods found in the New Zealand design code and FEMA P-58, the developed PSDR prediction model is comparable in accuracy and precision but simpler to use. The PFA prediction models, however, are more accurate and precise.",
